      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm going to be in Tokyo next week for a series of meetings. Can you help me put together a rough itinerary for my first few days? I'll be staying near Shibuya but most of my meetings are in the Marunouchi district. I need to make sure I account for travel time between the two, and I also need a few suggestions for quiet cafes near Marunouchi where I can catch up on emails between sessions.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! Here's a rough itinerary for your first few days in Tokyo. \n\nDay 1: Arrive in Tokyo and check into your hotel near Shibuya. After settling in, head to the Shibuya Crossing, the busiest pedestrian crossing in the world. It's a bit chaotic, but it's a great way to feel the pulse of Tokyo. From there, take a short train ride to Marunouchi. Make sure to grab a map of the Tokyo Metro, as it's the best way to navigate between districts. Once you arrive in Marunouchi, check into your hotel. After a short rest, head to a quiet cafe nearby, like \"Café de la Paix,\" where you can catch up on emails. \n\nDay 2: Start your day early and head to your first meeting in Marunouchi. After the meeting, grab a quick lunch at \"Kura Sushi,\" a sushi restaurant near your hotel. In the afternoon, visit the Tokyo Imperial Palace and its beautiful gardens. Afterward, head back to your hotel and relax. In the evening, explore the nightlife in the nearby Ginza district, known for its upscale shopping and entertainment. \n\nDay 3: Begin your day with a visit to the Tokyo National",
